{"type":"message-part","messageId":"705af50d-5683-4b73-91fb-4b704ba4dc33","role":"assistant","index":34,"part":{"type":"tool-attemptCompletion","toolCallId":"5eQHU3Xtj9pySTXy","state":"input-available","input":{"result":"I have built the Express.js API endpoint for Inconvo integration in `/home/user/inconvo-app/index.js`.\n\n### Implementation Details:\n- **Express Server**: Configured to listen on port `3001`.\n- **Route**: `POST /chat`\n  - **Validation**: Ensures the `message` field is present and non-empty. Returns HTTP 400 with `{ \"error\": \"message is required\" }` if validation fails.\n  - **Inconvo Integration**:\n    - Initializes the `Inconvo` client using `process.env.INCONVO_API_KEY`.\n    - Creates a conversation using `inconvo.agents.conversations.create` with `process.env.INCONVO_AGENT_ID`, `userId`, and `userContext: { organisationId: 1 }`.\n    - Retrieves the agent's response using `inconvo.agents.conversations.response.create`.\n    - Returns the full response object from Inconvo as JSON with HTTP 200.\n- **Environment**: Uses `dotenv` to load environment variables.\n\n### Verification:\n- Ran `node -c index.js` to verify syntax.\n- Started the server and confirmed it outputs \"Server listening on port 3001\".\n\nYou can start the server by running:\n```bash\ncd /home/user/inconvo-app\nnode index.js\n```"},"callProviderMetadata":{"vertex":{"thoughtSignature":""}}}}
